guess. u star is K inverse f.

00:18:02.410 --> 00:18:04.331
So that's cool.

00:18:04.331 --> 00:18:04.830
Shorter.

00:18:04.830 --> 00:18:06.530
It's shorter and better.

00:18:06.530 --> 00:18:15.400
K -- or its transpose -- U
minus u star plus a constant.

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:17.470
So I can forget that.

00:18:17.470 --> 00:18:20.130
I can forget this constant part.

00:18:20.130 --> 00:18:27.400
That's not important to us.

00:18:27.400 --> 00:18:33.500
So this simple identity
then has expressed

00:18:33.500 --> 00:18:45.820
our key discretization
approach here as finding the U,

00:18:45.820 --> 00:18:51.720
and we're going to call it U
star, that's nearest to u star.

00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:58.361
That's the great fact that makes
the whole subject pleasant.

00:18:58.361 --> 00:18:58.860
OK.

00:18:58.860 --> 00:19:04.160
So the winner U star
is then, by this,

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:06.570
since I'm minimizing
that expression,

00:19:06.570 --> 00:19:16.510
it's certainly the
nearest in the K norm --

00:19:16.510 --> 00:19:23.090
it's the nearest weighted by
K, somehow that K is important.

00:19:23.090 --> 00:19:30.090
That K is reflecting the
problem we're solving.

00:19:30.090 --> 00:19:38.490
That K is the energy or
whatever -- to U star.

00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:39.210
OK.

00:19:39.210 --> 00:19:41.940
That's the great conclusion.

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:43.880
You could say that's
the fundamental theorem

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:51.700
of this projection, error
estimates and stuff.

00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:54.110
So do you see that
we got to that?

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:58.130
The thing that minimizes
makes this as small as we can.

00:19:58.130 --> 00:20:04.340
So nearest is simply a
translation of what that says.

00:20:04.340 --> 00:20:07.840
Pick the capital U
that's closest to u star.

00:20:07.840 --> 00:20:08.770
OK.

00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:11.710
Now how does that help?

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:15.440
That helps because I want
to estimate the difference.

00:20:15.440 --> 00:20:26.950
So now I estimate the difference
of U star minus u star.

00:20:32.480 --> 00:20:36.010
So I'm trying to get a handle
on how different those are.

00:20:36.010 --> 00:20:44.420
How different is the -- so let
me take, in this case of, say,

00:20:44.420 --> 00:20:49.910
Laplace's equation or
the 1D case -- again,

00:20:49.910 --> 00:20:53.560
I'm speaking steady-state
boundary value problem.

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:58.150
So U star is the best
combination of these trial

00:20:58.150 --> 00:21:05.440
functions, capital U, and little
u star is the exact solution.

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:06.480
Let me draw a picture.

00:21:09.070 --> 00:21:13.600
So suppose I'm in 1D, 0 to 1.

00:21:13.600 --> 00:21:14.100
OK.

00:21:14.100 --> 00:21:18.280
Yeah, let me pick that
model problem again.

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:29.560
So minus the derivative
of c*du/dx is f of x.

00:21:29.560 --> 00:21:35.040
With boundary conditions.

00:21:35.040 --> 00:21:38.870
And I guess if I'm consistent
now, I should write u star,

00:21:38.870 --> 00:21:41.180
because it's the
winning solution.

00:21:41.180 --> 00:21:44.630
And suppose the boundary
conditions are 0 at both ends,

00:21:44.630 --> 00:21:46.150
and it does something.

00:21:46.150 --> 00:21:47.990
OK.

00:21:47.990 --> 00:21:48.970
So that's u star.

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:54.270
OK.

00:21:54.270 --> 00:21:57.020
So that's a
continuous case, which

00:21:57.020 --> 00:22:01.500
I'm drawing a picture
to represent what

00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:03.170
the solution might look like.

00:22:03.170 --> 00:22:03.890
OK.

00:22:03.890 --> 00:22:08.160
Now what about this
finite element stuff?

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:14.450
Suppose the phi_i's
are linear pieces.

00:22:14.450 --> 00:22:20.450
I'm going to do linear
finite element method.

00:22:20.450 --> 00:22:24.610
Then any combination
of these linear guys

00:22:24.610 --> 00:22:27.810
is going to be piecewise linear,
there's going to be a mesh.

00:22:27.810 --> 00:22:30.200
You know the set-up.

00:22:30.200 --> 00:22:33.940
It might look like that,
and have a value there.

00:22:33.940 --> 00:22:36.050
It might have a value
there, might have a value

00:22:36.050 --> 00:22:39.710
there, there, there, and there.

00:22:39.710 --> 00:22:41.770
OK.

00:22:41.770 --> 00:22:47.650
And let's suppose
this is the winning --

00:22:47.650 --> 00:22:52.880
doesn't look like
a winner to me,

00:22:52.880 --> 00:22:55.690
because I think it could
probably do better, but --

00:22:55.690 --> 00:22:57.390
capital U star.

00:22:57.390 --> 00:23:01.070
But remember that
we're measuring --

00:23:01.070 --> 00:23:04.210
what's the K norm stuff?

00:23:04.210 --> 00:23:07.150
I'm measuring the difference
between these two not

00:23:07.150 --> 00:23:11.860
pointwise, which would
be of course pleasant

00:23:11.860 --> 00:23:14.530
to say, OK, the distance
is just, you know,

00:23:14.530 --> 00:23:21.200
maybe the maximum distance
or the mean square error.

00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:24.200
That would be quite pleasant.

00:23:24.200 --> 00:23:30.280
But here the measure of
distance involves this K,

00:23:30.280 --> 00:23:35.740
which comes with the problem.

00:23:35.740 --> 00:23:41.510
So by distance here
I mean the distance

00:23:41.510 --> 00:23:45.320
between U star and u star.

00:23:45.320 --> 00:23:51.360
Can I write it with a
capital K there to indicate

00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:53.080
that that's the K norm?

00:23:53.080 --> 00:23:59.500
That's the norm in which this is
small, as small as can be made.

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:02.840
And what is the K norm for
this particular problem?

00:24:02.840 --> 00:24:08.450
Well it's the integral,
and involves the c,

00:24:08.450 --> 00:24:15.680
and it involves the U star prime
minus the u star prime square

00:24:15.680 --> 00:24:22.810
dx, integrated from 0 to 1.

00:24:22.810 --> 00:24:25.440
I'm just picking
this example problem

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:31.270
so that you get some idea of
how we're measuring the error.

00:24:31.270 --> 00:24:33.090
It's the natural
measure for the error.

00:24:33.090 --> 00:24:34.240
It's the energy measure.

00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:36.680
We're measuring error in energy.

00:24:36.680 --> 00:24:40.410
This is an energy expression.

00:24:40.410 --> 00:24:44.320
This thing, you know,
represents some kind

00:24:44.320 --> 00:24:50.140
of elastic bar or something,
so we're measuring

00:24:50.140 --> 00:24:51.910
the internal energy here.

00:24:51.910 --> 00:24:55.390
And notice in particular,
maybe the most important point

00:24:55.390 --> 00:25:00.180
is not the c of x, which just
comes along for the ride,

00:25:00.180 --> 00:25:08.990
but the fact that our measure of
the error is in the derivative.

00:25:08.990 --> 00:25:12.610
We're measuring error
in slopes, because those

00:25:12.610 --> 00:25:17.370
are the stresses in
the bar, and that's

00:25:17.370 --> 00:25:23.410
where the energy comes from,
internal strain energy.

00:25:23.410 --> 00:25:24.290
OK.

00:25:24.290 --> 00:25:32.470
So in other words, I have
this function u star,

00:25:32.470 --> 00:25:39.020
this curved guy, and I
have this function, which

00:25:39.020 --> 00:25:41.220
I'm thinking to be the winner.

00:25:41.220 --> 00:25:43.440
And again, it's the
winner in the sense

00:25:43.440 --> 00:25:45.670
that it minimizes this.

00:25:45.670 --> 00:25:47.470
This is the minimum.

00:25:47.470 --> 00:25:51.800
This is the expression that
we have some handle on,

00:25:51.800 --> 00:25:56.100
because we know that U
star, capital U star,

00:25:56.100 --> 00:25:59.080
will make that as
small as it can.

00:25:59.080 --> 00:26:01.610
It does not make small
the pointwise error.

00:26:04.850 --> 00:26:08.700
It might try, it
might accidentally --

00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:11.620
we hope it does of course --
get pointwise error right.

00:26:11.620 --> 00:26:17.060
But what it is constructed
to get right is energy error.

00:26:17.060 --> 00:26:17.960
Make that small.

00:26:17.960 --> 00:26:18.630
OK.

00:26:18.630 --> 00:26:22.860
So now the question is how do
we estimate the difference?

00:26:22.860 --> 00:26:23.550
OK.

00:26:23.550 --> 00:26:25.750
So now, here's
this key point, how

00:26:25.750 --> 00:26:29.060
do we estimate the difference.

00:26:29.060 --> 00:26:32.310
Again we're looking
at the error.

00:26:32.310 --> 00:26:39.330
By the way, I should have,
maybe I did, put a square there.

00:26:39.330 --> 00:26:42.380
That was the norm
squared, but of course,

00:26:42.380 --> 00:26:46.610
minimizing the norm -- you
realize why I don't want a big

00:26:46.610 --> 00:26:48.990
square root sign,
it's just clumsy.

00:26:48.990 --> 00:26:51.400
So I'm looking at
the square there.

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:52.115
OK.

00:26:52.115 --> 00:26:53.740
So now, how do you
estimate that thing?

00:26:53.740 --> 00:26:58.280
How do you estimate
the thing, knowing

00:26:58.280 --> 00:27:05.060
that this piecewise linear, that
came out of some finite element

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:10.940
calculation or some giant
code, is best possible?

00:27:10.940 --> 00:27:13.670
Well here's the idea.

00:27:13.670 --> 00:27:28.980
Look at a convenient candidate
that might not be the winner.

00:27:31.570 --> 00:27:36.340
Let me put, because this
was as small as possible,

00:27:36.340 --> 00:27:43.330
this is less than or
equal to U minus u star --

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:54.130
always in the correct measure
-- for every trial function U.

00:27:54.130 --> 00:27:59.380
This just says what I've
said now three ways,

00:27:59.380 --> 00:28:02.900
that U star's the
best in the K norm.

00:28:02.900 --> 00:28:10.940
Now I -- to get some bound
on this, I can take any U,

00:28:10.940 --> 00:28:15.530
I can take any U and estimate
its difference from U star,

00:28:15.530 --> 00:28:17.410
and that will give me a bound.

00:28:17.410 --> 00:28:21.800
In other words, I don't know
what this particular guy

00:28:21.800 --> 00:28:22.800
happened to be.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:31.770
Let me just jump
to the key idea.

00:28:31.770 --> 00:28:35.730
I know that that one is
better than the one --

00:28:35.730 --> 00:28:39.040
and if I had a
different color --

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:43.340
maybe this thing has
got another color.

00:28:48.500 --> 00:28:52.500
Okay, here's another color.

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:54.490
I know it's better
than, for example --

00:28:54.490 --> 00:29:00.050
I'm just going to pick one
piecewise linear trial function

00:29:00.050 --> 00:29:01.520
that's quite convenient.

00:29:01.520 --> 00:29:08.780
Pick the one that
interpolates the exact one.

00:29:08.780 --> 00:29:10.150
OK.

00:29:10.150 --> 00:29:15.040
Now for some reason, known
only to finite elements,

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:16.970
that wasn't the
finite element winner.

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:22.500
That wasn't U star, that was
another U. For example --

00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:29.620
so like, I'll put it in
blue here -- for example,

00:29:29.620 --> 00:29:38.760
take U to be the function
that interpolates u star,

00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:43.500
little u star, the function
that I've drawn here.

00:29:43.500 --> 00:29:50.020
Since our question is how close
can we get to the curved guy

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:54.825
by piecewise linear,
well, one choice

00:29:54.825 --> 00:29:58.455
is how close does
the interpolate come.

00:29:58.455 --> 00:30:00.160
It doesn't necessarily
come the closest.

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:00.980
Probably not.

00:30:00.980 --> 00:30:04.350
But it's in the right ballpark.

00:30:04.350 --> 00:30:06.590
So now I just ask
the question, and let

00:30:06.590 --> 00:30:11.660
me draw the same picture again.

00:30:11.660 --> 00:30:16.300
I have a function
and I interpolate it

00:30:16.300 --> 00:30:19.990
by piecewise linear guys.

00:30:22.530 --> 00:30:27.330
So piecewise linear
function there.

00:30:27.330 --> 00:30:32.520
And so this is a comparison
between the u star

00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:41.840
and its interpolate, which
is my candidate U that I'm

00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:45.670
recommending as a trial.

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:49.260
And now it's a pure
approximation question.

00:30:49.260 --> 00:30:53.880
You see, we no longer have to
know all about finite elements,

00:30:53.880 --> 00:30:56.470
we don't have to know anything
about finite elements.

00:30:56.470 --> 00:31:02.540
We're just asking the question:
if you give me a function,

00:31:02.540 --> 00:31:07.750
and you compare it with the
piecewise linear interpolate,

00:31:07.750 --> 00:31:09.940
how far apart are they?

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:12.980
How far apart?

00:31:12.980 --> 00:31:21.150
And let me call the step
size h, and of course,

00:31:21.150 --> 00:31:22.760
could be unequal steps.

00:31:22.760 --> 00:31:25.270
It could be unstructured mesh.

00:31:25.270 --> 00:31:28.860
Everything works here.

00:31:28.860 --> 00:31:34.410
Now we come to just a basic sort
of understanding of calculus.

00:31:34.410 --> 00:31:41.540
How close does a curve
come from the chord?

00:31:41.540 --> 00:31:43.720
Really, that's what
it's come down to.

00:31:43.720 --> 00:31:49.210
How close is a curved
function from a chord?

00:31:49.210 --> 00:31:51.490
I can even blow that up.

00:31:51.490 --> 00:31:55.050
So here I have some
curve going up,

00:31:55.050 --> 00:31:57.450
and compare that with the chord.

00:32:01.430 --> 00:32:04.010
And this distance here is h.

00:32:04.010 --> 00:32:12.950
Anybody know?

00:32:12.950 --> 00:32:17.230
So I'm just looking
for something like,

00:32:17.230 --> 00:32:21.930
is the difference of order
h, is it of order h square,

00:32:21.930 --> 00:32:23.830
is it of order e to the h.

00:32:23.830 --> 00:32:27.360
What the distance
between the two?

00:32:31.600 --> 00:32:34.560
And you could imagine it's a
parabola, because I'm focusing

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:36.270
down on just a little piece.

00:32:36.270 --> 00:32:39.690
I take a little parabola,
a little h piece of it,

00:32:39.690 --> 00:32:43.050
and I compare it
with a chord, what's

00:32:43.050 --> 00:32:45.000
the distance between the two?

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.650
That distance there.

00:32:47.650 --> 00:32:53.220
Well your eye probably tells
you that it's smaller than h,

00:32:53.220 --> 00:32:56.750
because h was this
big, and I'm only

00:32:56.750 --> 00:32:59.190
looking this big vertically.

00:32:59.190 --> 00:33:06.250
So this distance, that distance
there, maximum distance,

00:33:06.250 --> 00:33:08.240
is of order h square.

00:33:12.730 --> 00:33:14.100
But that's not the question.

00:33:16.870 --> 00:33:20.740
The question is how
far apart are these,

00:33:20.740 --> 00:33:24.570
how far apart of the
these in this measure?

00:33:27.230 --> 00:33:30.170
How far apart are the slopes?

00:33:30.170 --> 00:33:36.620
Because the K norm is dealing
with the slopes, and not

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:38.420
the function itself.

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:43.500
So more important than the
distance is the error in slope,

00:33:43.500 --> 00:33:47.770
and would you want to
guess what that's like?

00:33:52.380 --> 00:33:55.860
What's your guess on that,
the error in the slope?

00:33:55.860 --> 00:33:58.470
Now the slopes are not going
to be as good as the function,

00:33:58.470 --> 00:33:59.700
as always.

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:03.420
Slopes are one derivative
higher, you lose something,

00:34:03.420 --> 00:34:07.930
you get order h.

00:34:07.930 --> 00:34:11.590
So that's the error.

00:34:14.310 --> 00:34:16.830
Let's see, I hope
I'm right here.

00:34:16.830 --> 00:34:17.500
Yeah.

00:34:17.500 --> 00:34:19.370
I think that's right.

00:34:19.370 --> 00:34:25.440
There I was speaking
pointwise, and then I've

00:34:25.440 --> 00:34:28.610
got to integrate it
over the whole interval

00:34:28.610 --> 00:34:30.670
here, a unit interval.

00:34:30.670 --> 00:34:38.450
So if I square it, of course,
I'm going to get h square,

00:34:38.450 --> 00:34:41.192
and then if I integrated
it, I still have h square,

00:34:41.192 --> 00:34:43.150
and then when I take the
square root, I have h.

00:34:43.150 --> 00:34:45.530
So h is the right quantity.

00:34:49.150 --> 00:34:54.940
If I can put down here what our
conclusion was from this method

00:34:54.940 --> 00:35:03.640
by taking capital U to
be this convenient --

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:06.910
not the only choice,
but a convenient choice,

00:35:06.910 --> 00:35:09.290
just to get an idea
what the error might be.

00:35:09.290 --> 00:35:11.760
And then the error
from the actual U star

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:14.100
is got to be
better, our estimate

00:35:14.100 --> 00:35:22.310
is order of h for this
particular application.

00:35:22.310 --> 00:35:23.810
This particular application.

00:35:23.810 --> 00:35:32.100
That's the error in
energy norm in the slopes.

00:35:37.690 --> 00:35:41.380
So the theory of finite
elements would go ahead

00:35:41.380 --> 00:35:47.540
to try to show that the error
in the distance between them,

00:35:47.540 --> 00:35:52.320
in the displacement you
could say, is h square.

00:35:52.320 --> 00:35:56.710
But that's not so easy, and I
won't be able to do it here.

00:35:56.710 --> 00:36:02.250
Why is it not easy to say that
the error in the displacement

00:36:02.250 --> 00:36:03.750
is of order h square?

00:36:03.750 --> 00:36:09.350
It's certainly true for
this interpolate, right.

00:36:09.350 --> 00:36:12.530
There's no question that the
interpolate you could easily

00:36:12.530 --> 00:36:17.190
see is h square, order h
square away from the function.

00:36:17.190 --> 00:36:25.950
But the point is that
capital U star was not

00:36:25.950 --> 00:36:30.330
the best in staying
near the function,

00:36:30.330 --> 00:36:33.600
it was only the best in
staying near the slope.

00:36:33.600 --> 00:36:40.440
So I don't have this
crutch to lean on here.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:45.760
This is in the K norm, and
not in the mean square norm.

00:36:45.760 --> 00:36:49.960
It's in a norm that
deals with slope, but not

00:36:49.960 --> 00:36:53.901
with just plain
displacement distance.

00:36:53.901 --> 00:36:54.400
OK.

00:36:54.400 --> 00:36:57.330
Maybe that's made the point.

00:36:57.330 --> 00:37:03.650
And this is the part of finite
element theory just to do that.

00:37:03.650 --> 00:37:05.280
OK.

00:37:05.280 --> 00:37:11.280
If I could take a
minute about notation,

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:19.650
because the notation that
I've used here of a K

00:37:19.650 --> 00:37:21.130
is really a matrix notation.

00:37:24.750 --> 00:37:27.660
You don't truly see it
in finite element papers.

00:37:27.660 --> 00:37:30.040
For me, it's clear, right?

00:37:30.040 --> 00:37:34.160
I mean that identity
was quite clear

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:36.280
from vectors and matrices.

00:37:36.280 --> 00:37:41.720
But with finite elements I'm
really dealing with functions.

00:37:41.720 --> 00:37:49.610
So it's not fair to use
matrix notation, you know,

00:37:49.610 --> 00:37:54.150
when it's integrals, and
derivatives, and functions

00:37:54.150 --> 00:37:56.090
that are involve here.

00:37:56.090 --> 00:37:59.910
You know, these are functions,
and the actual solution

00:37:59.910 --> 00:38:01.140
is a function.

00:38:01.140 --> 00:38:13.500
